outer membrane","Connected solely to peptidoglycan layer","Embedded in cytoplasm only","Floating freely in periplasmic space"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EBacterial flagella are complex molecular machines that enable motility. They are \u003Cstrong\u003Eanchored through both cell wall and membrane\u003C/strong\u003E via the basal body complex, which provides structural stability and allows for rotational movement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAttached only to outer membrane\u003C/strong\u003E - This would not provide sufficient structural support for flagellar rotation\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConnected solely to peptidoglycan layer\u003C/strong\u003E - Anchoring through multiple layers is necessary for proper function\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEmbedded in cytoplasm only\u003C/strong\u003E - Flagella must extend outside the cell to enable movement\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFloating freely in periplasmic space\u003C/strong\u003E - This would not allow for directed movement\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe basal body complex spans both the cell membrane and cell wall, anchoring the flagellum securely. This arrangement allows for the mechanical force of flagellar rotation to propel the bacterium through its environment.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Bacterial flagella are anchored in the cell wall and cell membrane via the basal body complex","Flagella are composed primarily of the protein flagellin, not lipopolysaccharides","Flagella are found in both gram-positive and gram-negative bacteria and serve as important virulence factors"],"references":["Subramanian S, Kearns DB. Functional Regulators of Bacterial Flagella. Annu Rev Microbiol. 2019 Sep 8;73:225-246. doi: 10.1146/annurev-micro-020518-115725. Epub 2019 May 